In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims September 1, 2014, as Labor Day in the United States. He highlights the importance of honoring the legacy of working men and women who have contributed to the country's progress. The President acknowledges the hard work, responsibility, and sacrifice of American workers in various sectors, stating that the economy grows best from the middle out. He recognizes the efforts of past generations in fighting for workplace protections and rights, such as the 40-hour workweek, overtime pay, safe working conditions, collective bargaining, and minimum wage laws. President Obama also emphasizes the need to continue working towards economic growth, strengthening the middle class, and providing opportunities for all Americans. He mentions efforts to boost economic mobility, ensure fair wages, eliminate pay discrimination, combat unfair labor practices, and defend collective bargaining rights. The President concludes by calling upon all public officials and people of the United States to observe Labor Day with appropriate programs and activities that honor the contributions and resilience of working Americans.